{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505046"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2398"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2398"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0.06,0.09,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114716"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2398"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96719"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4075"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48263"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114716"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-month history of amenorrhoea. Over the past 12 months, she has experienced irregular menstrual cycles occurring every 45 to 50 days with lighter bleeding. She reports recurring headaches, difficulty sleeping, increased sweating, and reduced libido. She has no significant medical history apart from two previous caesarean sections at ages 25 and 30 years. She does not take any regular medications. She exercises moderately for 15 to 30 minutes daily and has not experienced any weight changes. Her partner had a vasectomy three years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination is unremarkable. Laboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone: 300 IU/L (4-30)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELuteinising hormone: 140 IU/L (10-75)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProlactin: 20 \u03bcg/L (\u0026lt;25)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETestosterone: 1.0 nmol/L (0.5-2.6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOestradiol: 37 pmol/L (46-607)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA similar FSH result was obtained one month ago.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Premature ovarian insufficiency","Functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea","Pituitary adenoma","Late-onset congenital adrenal hyperplasia","Polycystic ovarian syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of premature ovarian insufficiency (POI), defined as loss of ovarian function before age 40. The diagnosis is supported by amenorrhoea for more than four months, markedly elevated FSH levels (\u0026gt;30 IU/L) on two occasions at least four weeks apart, elevated LH, and low oestradiol. The presence of vasomotor symptoms (sweating), sleep disturbance, and reduced libido are typical menopausal symptoms seen in POI. Most cases are idiopathic, though autoimmune diseases, genetic disorders, and iatrogenic causes are recognised contributors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPremature ovarian insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis based on the constellation of clinical features and laboratory findings. The markedly elevated FSH of 300 IU/L on two occasions, combined with amenorrhoea and menopausal symptoms in a woman under 40, confirms this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunctional hypothalamic amenorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with low or normal FSH and LH levels due to suppression of gonadotropin-releasing hormone pulsatility, often triggered by stress, excessive exercise, or eating disorders. This patient\u0027s gonadotropins are markedly elevated, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPituitary adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E causing amenorrhoea would typically present with elevated prolactin and low gonadotropins due to suppression of gonadotropin-releasing hormone. This patient\u0027s prolactin is normal and gonadotropins are elevated, excluding this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELate-onset congenital adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E presents with signs of androgen excess including hirsutism and elevated testosterone levels. This patient\u0027s testosterone is normal and she lacks clinical features of hyperandrogenism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovarian syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with irregular periods rather than amenorrhoea, and is associated with normal to slightly elevated FSH, elevated LH:FSH ratio, and clinical or biochemical features of hyperandrogenism such as acne or hirsutism. The markedly elevated FSH and presence of menopausal symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of POI focuses on hormone replacement therapy (HRT) to alleviate symptoms and prevent long-term complications. Additional management includes calcium and vitamin D supplementation, regular bone density monitoring, cardiovascular risk assessment, and psychological support to address the emotional impact of the diagnosis, particularly regarding fertility concerns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Premature ovarian insufficiency is diagnosed by FSH \u003E30 IU/L on two occasions 4-6 weeks apart with amenorrhoea for \u003E4 months in women under 40 years.","Common symptoms of premature ovarian insufficiency include vasomotor symptoms, sleep disturbance, and reduced libido.","Most cases of premature ovarian insufficiency are idiopathic but can be associated with autoimmune conditions, genetic disorders, or iatrogenic causes."],"references":["Alzubaidi NH, Chapin HL, Vanderhoof VH, et al. Meeting the needs of young women with secondary amenorrhea and spontaneous premature ovarian failure. Obstet Gynecol 2002;99:720. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11978278/","De Vos M, Devroey P, Fauser BC. Primary ovarian insufficiency. Lancet 2010;376:911. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(10)60355-8/abstract","Nguyen HH, Milat F, Vincent A. Premature ovarian insufficiency in general practice: Meeting the needs of women. Aust Fam Physician. 2017 Jun;46(6):360-366. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28609590/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96719"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2398"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96719"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-19T12:30:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T12:32:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2398"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114716"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic